        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              I thought when Ned was killed - I suppose Robert too - that Martin was aiming to tell a multi-generational story, and that Robb, Jon, Bran, and possibly their children would be the real protagonists. Instead, he has shown a remarkable commitment (and possibly relish) to screwing over the &quot;good guys&quot; in as many ways as possible, with no trace of the usual humor or sympathy that makes it an enjoyable fan experience. Why follow the series to its end? Don't get me wrong- I will, as I enjoy the world setting and his writing is perfectly comfortable- but I'm not interested in investing any great emotion in the characters anymore.<br /><br />I'm only halfway through book 4 at this point, and I've tried to dodge around spoilers in this discussion, but it seems that Martin isn't winning back any of your hearts. <br /><br />I've had a couple of good rants with myself in the car about Cersei and Sansa. Joffrey was horrible, but I had a strong sense he would not be allowed to live. I also fantasized for a while about exterminating the Freys.<br /><br />I am holding out hope for Arya, although she seems pretty broken. Where is her wolf? Will they be reunited into some crazy fighting team? Was Syrio really killed in King's Landing? <br /><br />I'm pretty scared for Brienne- she has all the hallmarks of the tragic hero, and Martin is unflinching in his abuse of good characters.<br /><br />I like the Onion Knight too- I'm not sure exactly what has happened to him, but I hope he isn't just discarded.<br /><br />Finally, can one of these newfound magic users forge a replacement hand for Jaime? Make sure it's after his self-examination and redemption are complete, so he doesn't backslide.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
